/-
# `Dregg2.Crypto.MlDsaSigVerAcvp` -- the ML-DSA-65 verify KAT floor, anchored to **NIST-published ACVP vectors**

This module pins the COMPLETE NIST ACVP `ML-DSA-sigVer-FIPS204` test group for the parameter set and
interface `verifyCore` implements, and proves the Lean verifier reproduces NIST's own accept/reject
verdict on every one of them.

## Provenance (exact, verifiable -- nothing here is crate-generated or hand-written)

* Repository: `https://github.com/usnistgov/ACVP-Server` (NIST's own ACVP server / vector repository),
  branch `master`, fetched 2026-07-20 via `raw.githubusercontent.com`.
* File: `gen-val/json-files/ML-DSA-sigVer-FIPS204/internalProjection.json`
* Downloaded-file digests -- md5 `2b4b09d4322ec83c71e0e1e20e26c7fa`,
  sha256 `85827fd9f058d617b956301d342f2792d66ff188987ccce87f014f0bdb282457`.
* Group: `tgId = 3` (`testType = "AFT"`, `parameterSet = "ML-DSA-65"`, `signatureInterface = "external"`,
  `preHash = "pure"`, `externalMu = false`) -- the group that matches `verifyCore`, which implements FIPS 204
  Algorithm 3 (external `ctx` framing `0x00 || |ctx| || ctx || M`) around Algorithm 8 `verify_internal`.
* Test cases: `tcId` 31-45 -- ALL 15 of the group (3 expected-accept, 12 expected-reject; the
  reject reasons NIST assigns cover `modified signature - z`, `- hint`, `- commitment`, and
  `modified message`). Message lengths range 1-8192 bytes and context lengths 0-255 bytes, so the
  `|ctx|` framing byte and the SHAKE block boundaries are exercised by NIST's own choice of inputs.

The `pk` / `message` / `context` / `signature` fields are pinned VERBATIM as the lowercase hex strings that
appear in the ACVP JSON (transcribed programmatically, never retyped), and `expected` is NIST's own
`testPassed` boolean. Pinning the hex verbatim keeps the constants here diff-able against the published
JSON by eye; `hexBytes` decodes them at evaluation time.

## The statement

`verifyCore_matches_acvp_sigVer` says: for EVERY pinned vector, `verifyCore pk msg ctx sig` equals NIST's
`testPassed`. This is a `List.all` over the pinned batch -- a single `native_decide` over the compiled
`def`s, so a wrong accept OR a wrong reject anywhere in the group breaks it. It is a KAT (a finite batch of
concrete inputs), NOT a `forall`-quantified correctness theorem; the `forall` direction lives in
`VerifyCoreEqSpec`.

## Residual

`native_decide` runs the COMPILED `def`s, so this theorem carries the per-declaration compiler-trust axiom
`verifyCore_matches_acvp_sigVer._native.native_decide.ax` (the v4.30 realization of `Lean.ofReduceBool` /
`Lean.trustCompiler`) -- the SAME residual `Keccak`, `MlDsaRing`, `MlDsaCodec` and `MlDsaVerifyReal` already
name. The `#guard` shape checks are commands with no proof term and add NO axiom. No `sorry`, no user
`axiom`, no toy substitute.
-/
import Dregg2.Crypto.MlDsaVerifyReal

namespace Dregg2.Crypto.MlDsaSigVerAcvp

open Dregg2.Crypto.MlDsaVerifyReal (verifyCore)

set_option maxRecDepth 1000000
set_option maxHeartbeats 0

/-- One lowercase/uppercase hex nibble to its `[0,16)` value; `none` on a non-hex char. -/
def hexNibble? (c : Char) : Option UInt8 :=
  if '0' <= c && c <= '9' then some (UInt8.ofNat (c.toNat - '0'.toNat))
  else if 'a' <= c && c <= 'f' then some (UInt8.ofNat (c.toNat - 'a'.toNat + 10))
  else if 'A' <= c && c <= 'F' then some (UInt8.ofNat (c.toNat - 'A'.toNat + 10))
  else none

/-- Decode a hex char list to bytes; `none` on an odd length or any non-hex char (fail-closed). -/
def decodeHexChars : List Char -> Option (List UInt8)
  | [] => some []
  | [_] => none
  | a :: b :: rest => do
      let hi <- hexNibble? a
      let lo <- hexNibble? b
      let tl <- decodeHexChars rest
      return (hi * 16 + lo) :: tl

/-- Decode a hex string to bytes, `[]` on malformed input (never reached: every pinned string is
even-length hex straight out of the ACVP JSON, which the `wellFormed` `#guard` below checks). -/
def hexBytes (s : String) : List UInt8 := (decodeHexChars s.toList).getD []

/-- A NIST ACVP `ML-DSA-sigVer-FIPS204` test case, fields verbatim from the published JSON.
`expected` is NIST's `testPassed`. -/
structure SigVerVec where
  tcId : Nat
  pk : String
  msg : String
  ctx : String
  sig : String
  expected : Bool
  /-- NIST's own `reason` string for the case. -/
  reason : String

/-- `verifyCore` run on one decoded vector agrees with NIST's `testPassed`. -/
def agreesWithAcvp (v : SigVerVec) : Bool :=
  verifyCore (hexBytes v.pk) (hexBytes v.msg) (hexBytes v.ctx) (hexBytes v.sig) == v.expected

/-- Every pinned hex field decodes (even length, all hex) and carries the FIPS 204 ML-DSA-65 sizes. -/
def wellFormed (v : SigVerVec) : Bool :=
  (decodeHexChars v.pk.toList).isSome && (decodeHexChars v.msg.toList).isSome &&
  (decodeHexChars v.ctx.toList).isSome && (decodeHexChars v.sig.toList).isSome &&
  (hexBytes v.pk).length == 1952 && (hexBytes v.sig).length == 3309 &&
  (hexBytes v.ctx).length <= 255

